I applied to Jane Street's quantitative trader position in the september of 2017. Having received a superday after completing an arduous preliminary rounds of interviews, I made sure to prepare well to be face to face with a real panel of senior traders. I prepared a showcase of my mathematical proofs and programming projects to present. As I walked in, I was hardly even greeted by the daunting panel of mathematical geniuses. Without introduction, they proceeded to ask me about how I spent my time as one of the top financial mathematics and statistics students at the Wharton School at the University of Pennsylvania. 

Apparently my experience as an analyst a Quantitative Analyst at Barclay‚Äôs, compact proof for Fermat's Last Theorem, and the prestige as a first place finish at the William Lowell Putnam Mathematical Competition did not seem to impress them as they just chuckled and proceeded to throw my 119 page CV into the trash. Many people always ask me how I was able to get a job at Goldman Sachs as a 16 year old who skipped 3 grades of high school. They think I got it because of my scholarly records, but no the key is the interview.

As I sat in the Goldman CEO's office in front of the board of directors reviewing my application, the CEO asks me "Why should you be a good candidate for this job?" They seemed bored but I replied "Well I was born a child prodigy, placed 1st in my state spelling bee for three consecutive years, I can speak eight different languages not counting Latin, play four different instruments, I skipped grades 4 through 6, and graduated my high school as valedictorian at the age of 14. I then worked as an intern at both Telsa, and NASA." Suddenly the room burst into laughter and many of board instantly started scribbling down "No" near the application check marks. The CEO says "Sorry but you are just not the type we are looking for." But then I said "Excuse me but I wasn't finished... I went to Penn for undergrad" The CEO looked at me like an idiot and said "So....?" Then I replied with a smile "And I did M&T" An audible gasp let out by the board was so loud the secretary had to come in.
